CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F313A1778501469
OL,3,CWhat is an 'orderly' replacement of
OL,4,CStarmer?
OL,6,FIf it is an absolute car crash then
OL,7,Fthe consensus of MPs and ministers
OL,8,Fthat Starmer can stay a few more weeks
OL,9,Fand months will evaporate, and the
OL,10,Faccidental rebel Catherine West would
OL,11,Fsecure her 81 nominations to be the
OL,12,Fstalking horse challenger.
OL,14,FStarmer would be fighting for his
OL,15,Fpolitical life.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G7/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,314,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31308
SC,0008
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F313A1778501469
OL,3,CWhat is an 'orderly' replacement of
OL,4,CStarmer?
OL,6,FBut I have been briefed to expect a
OL,7,Fspeech that shows contrition, that
OL,8,FStarmer "gets it", but that it is too
OL,9,Fsoon for him to come up with a bold
OL,10,Fand unifying new vision for the
OL,11,Fcountry, not least because he avowedly
OL,12,Fhates doing "the vision thing".
OL,14,FIn other words, the speech will
OL,15,Fprobably be a bit of a "meh", neither
OL,16,Fone thing or another, neither
OL,17,Fhastening his exit or cancelling it.
OL,19,FWhich, possibly, for Starmer, in his
OL,20,Fcurrent dire straits, would be a win.
OL,26,@pD@IOUpD@QO]tD@MOUtD@^O]wD@XOUwD@\O]
